'''Using get() to Access values'''

alien_0 = {'color': 'green', 'speed': 'slow'}
# print(alien_0['points'])    # Key error

point_value = alien_0.get('points', 'No point value assigned.')
print(point_value)  # We get a clean message instead of an error.

# NOTE: If you leave out the second argument in the call to get() and
# the key doesn’t exist, Python will return the value None.
# The special value None means “no value exists.” 
# This is not an error: it’s a special value meant to indicate the absence of a value.


